“Yes, Captain. They should be on their way by now, they were still in the canteen picking up their rations.” At exactly 0500, the Exodus Company gathered at the truck park. Shaw climbed onto a crate and began to speak.
“We are being redeployed to the advanced base I-131, fifty miles outside Ianlos. Our task is to support the ongoing siege and later attack on Ianlos to drive out the rebels. There, we will establish a base at the foot of the mountains,” Shaw explained. “Break up into your teams and mount up.”
The company broke up into the respective teams, and the soldiers were assigned to the tanks by the sergeants. Cohren climbed onto one of the tanks further up in the convoy, where he met Nemic, Craith, and two new recruits. Cohren remembered their arrival a few days ago, but knew little about them. He sat to the side and let his legs dangle, adjusting his backpack and the radio, which was connected to his headphones and throat microphone.
“Hey Cohren, is Snowball still with Harris?” Nemic asked after they had settled in.
“Do you mean the rooster he stole?” Cohren remembered the morning when they took the animal from a farmer's farm. “Yes, I think so.”
Cohren looked over to one of the other tanks and spotted Harris with his group. From the corner of his eye, he could see the movement of a small rooster searching its surroundings by constantly turning its head.
"Yes, he's still with him," Cohren replied as the tank's hatch opened and the commander came into view.
"All tanks are moving out," the commander spoke slowly and calmly into his headset. The engines of the convoy of tanks and Strykers roared to life as they began to move. Cohren's Kronos tank shook as the brakes were released and they fell into formation. The tanks moved in a wedge formation across the Itania Plain. Despite the frozen wetlands and snow-covered forests due to the winter storms, mud was ubiquitous.
After about an hour, one of the recruits, whom Cohren knew was named Orson, began to speak. "Lieutenant, you've been here since the start of the war, right?"
"Yes, Operation Firestorm," Cohren replied. "We thought it would be over in a few weeks, but we underestimated it."
“Underestimated is strongly understated,” Nemic interjected into the conversation. “We weren't prepared for their arsenal and the large number of soldiers. They destroyed the UFS Revenant in the first two weeks and the Erebus just last month. We should even see them on our way.”
“I stand firmly on the side of the Federation,” Orson said defiantly. “I won't let these terrorists intimidate me.”
“You say that now. But I've seen that most 18-year-old recruits like you quickly take cover as soon as they hear a shot,” Craith explained.
“We'll see about that,” Cohren laughed. Orson ended the conversation.
“Exodus XO, Exodus CO,” Cohren's radio crackled. “We're receiving heat signatures, about 300 meters away, 20 degrees to the right.”
Cohren moved up to the tank and put on his special glasses. When he switched them to "heat vision," he could recognize the signatures in the distance.
“Yes, I see them,” Cohren replied over his throat microphone.
“Are they hostile?” asked the other recruit, Natayla.
“I can't tell,” Cohren replied. He reached for his microphone and said: “Exodus Company, don't fire until under fire. Let's lure them out.”
As they approached, the point-like heat signatures took shape. As they got closer, one of them quickly ran to get something and then rushed back to the small hill where the others were. The figures lay on the ground, getting into firing position.
"We have enemy contact," Shaw shouted over the radio as orange tracer rounds were fired from the hill. As the tanks came under fire, the infantry jumped down and took cover. A rocket whizzed by and hit the ground behind the formation, exploding and scattering debris onto one of the tanks. Another hit a Stryker, an APS-Cerberus, and exploded. The crew quickly climbed out and took cover as the ammunition flew through the air.
"Iron 1-2 and 1-3, 25 degrees right, 300 meters. Open fire," the commander of the tank convoy shouted over the radio. Iron 1-2 and 1-3 opened fire, grenades flew towards the hill and exploded, sending mud and rock flying into the air.
"Send in the Sentis," Knoxx called out, observing the hill with binoculars. The rear door of a Cerberus opened, and an unarmed soldier came out, wearing a special headset. He called out orders into a square microphone, and two Sentis, officially called Sentinels, stormed out. Their thin, metallic arms and legs swung forward as they sprinted, carrying their weapons on their backs.
"Kill or capture?" Craith asked, watching.
"Looks like a capture," Cohren guessed, as the two Sentinels disappeared into the ash and smoke. Shouts and shots echoed from the hill, but quickly subsided. A short time later, the two Sentinels returned, dragging someone behind them, whose boots left tracks in the ground. After returning to the safety of the convoy, they threw the figure to the ground. It groaned in pain as it landed hard in the mud and snow.
Shaw went to the figure who was trying to get up. Then he turned to one of the Sentinels. “How many?”
“Three dead, Sir,” the Sentinel replied. “The rest fled on foot.”
Shaw nodded and turned to Cohren and Craith, who were standing nearby. “Get rid of this guy for me!”
